They do have fat, but it's more of a food reserve than insulation. Most
birds have down under their contour feathers, like a down vest. It's
quite effective. They also have a relatively high metabolism that
generates plenty of heat. Finally, if it gets too cold, some birds go
into torpor at night, a hibernation-like state of reduced metabolism
that lowers body temperature and uses much less energy.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Furthermore, they don't have heater in their nests!
">

Nests are generally used only for incubating eggs and raising chicks.
They're typically abandoned when the chicks fledge.
