Indeed she does. In our haste to "help" wild animals, it's easy to
forget that every bit of their behavior has been honed by millennia of
evolution. If it didn't work, they wouldn't be here. It's that simple.

That said, in marginal situations some individuals will perish. That's
normal, too, and species' reproductive strategies compensate to keep
their populations stable (as long as we don't mess with their habitat
too much).

As humans, we tend to focus on individuals. Nature, though, deals with
species, and individual organisms are expendable, especially if their
instincts aren't a good match for their lifestyles. Helping the weak
survive doesn't strengthen a species' gene pool.
</POST>
